Exoplanet Data

We will be working with the default data set on exoplanets (planets orbiting stars outside our Solar System). The data is described in the Exoplanet Chapter of the Course Notes. We will only be exploring the mass, radius, and discovery method variables.

The variables we will be working with are defined below. See the course notes for more details.

planet = Planet Name
method = Method by which the planet was first identified
radius = Planet Radius (units: Earth Radius)
mass = Approximate or Minimum Planet Mass (units: Earth Mass)

Questions

Question 1

Make a scatter plot with radius (the estimate of the planet radius) on the x-axis and mass (the estimate of the planet mass) on the vertical axis.

  ggplot(planets) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = radius, y = mass)) +
  xlab("Radius (Earth Radius") +
  ylab("Mass (Earth Mass)") +
  ggtitle("Exoplanets Mass vs. Radius",
  subtitle = "Using NASA Explanet Archive Data")

Question 2

When variables are strongly skewed to the right (there are more observatons much larger than the median than there are observations much lower than the median) and when all observations are positive, it often aids visualization to examine the data on the log scale. Take your code from the previous plot and add the layers provided below. Describe how the plot changes.

  ggplot(planets, aes(x = radius, y = mass)) +
  geom_point()+
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  xlab("Radius (Earth Radius") +
  ylab("Mass (Earth Mass)") +
  ggtitle("Exoplanets Mass vs. Radius",
          subtitle = "Using NASA Explanet Archive Data")

Question 3

Make a scatter plot like the previous problem, but use the color aesthetic for method (discovery method).

  ggplot(planets, aes(x = radius, y = mass, color = method)) +
  geom_point()+
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  xlab("Radius") +
  ylab("Mass (Earth Mass)") +
  ggtitle("Exoplanets Mass vs. Radius",
          subtitle="Using NASA Explanet Archive Data")

Question 5

Another way to display differences by discovery method is to separate the plot into multiple panels (or facets) and plot different subsets of the data in each. We are going to look at planet mass versus radius again. Add a comment to say what the code on the next line does where indicated.

## uncomment and complete code below
# 
  ggplot(planets, aes(x=radius, y=mass)) +
  geom_point() +
  ## ADD A COMMENT SAYING WHAT THE NEXT LINE DOES
  # Response:Adds a smooth line that is fitted to the data
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE) +
  ## ADD A COMMENT SAYING WHAT THE NEXT LINE DOES
  # Response:Creates separate subplots of the data, (based on method of discovery)
  facet_wrap(~method) +
  xlab("Radius") +
  ylab("Mass (Earth Mass)") +
  ggtitle("Exoplanets Mass vs. Radius",
          subtitle="Using NASA Explanet Archive Data")
